article.description: Charlotte won on the road for the first time this season, getting 24 points from Sheri Sam and 17 from Tammy Sutton-Brown in a 77-66 victory at New York.
article.headline: Charlotte gets first road win of season; Baranova hurt
article.linkText: Sting get first road win of season at N.Y.; Baranova hurt
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Assured of having the worst record in the WNBA,
the Charlotte Sting are using the final games this year to prepare
for next season.
	   Charlotte won on the road for the first time this season,
getting 24 points from Sheri Sam and 17 from Tammy Sutton-Brown in
a 77-66 victory Thursday night over the New York Liberty.
	   "We're just going out there and having fun, and at the same
time trying to get better and build for next year," Sam said. "We
work hard every day.
	   "We've been in games, we haven't had the ability to close games
out. And we're learning to do that now, and just build for next
year. Being in situations, and knowing next year how to handle
it."
	   Charlotte (6-27), which lost its first 16 road games, closed
with a 24-8 run to avoid becoming just the second team in WNBA
history to finish winless away from home. The 1998 Washington
Mystics lost all 15 road games.
	   "It's good to finally get it, even if it's the last game," Sam
said. "We didn't want to go the whole year without getting one
road win."
	   Becky Hammon scored 20 points and Vickie Johnson had 16 for New
York (18-15), which has lost consecutive games after winning a
season-high five straight.
	   "I didn't think we played very well," Liberty coach Pat Coyle
said. "We lost our composure, and this time of year that can't
happen. We have our work cut out for us the next couple of days."
	   After Elena Baranova made two free throws to give New York a
58-54 lead with 8:49 left, Charlotte scored six straight points to
take the lead for good. Kelly Mazzante hit a 3-pointer, Teana
Miller made one of two free throws and Adrienne Goodson a layup to
give Charlotte a 60-58 lead with 6½ minutes remaining.
	   Johnson missed a pair of free throws, and Mazzante hit another 3
to push the Sting's lead to five points with 6 minutes left.
Johnson made a layup with 4½ minutes left to cut the Liberty's
deficit to 65-62, but Charlotte scored seven straight points over
the next two minutes to take a 10-point lead. New York got no
closer than eight in the final two minutes.
	   The Liberty, who close the season at Indiana on Saturday night
before hosting the Fever on Tuesday in the opener of the playoffs,
shot 37 percent.
	   "We just have to let this go and not dwell on it," Johnson
said. "Look at film tomorrow and correct the mistakes and move
forward.
	   "We have one more game left. When we go to Indiana we need to
make a statement, and let them know we're ready to play."
	   Baranova left the game due to a sprained right ankle with 3½
minutes remaining and did not return. The Liberty are already
without All-Star center Ann Wauters, who broke a bone in her right
hand at Charlotte on Aug. 12 and will miss at least the first round
of the playoffs.
	   In a game meaningless for the postseason, all five New York
starters played at least 23 minutes -- with three playing more than
30.
	   "We have an eight-man rotation and those people are going to
play the minutes," Coyle said. "If we had five games left, two
left, one left. It doesn't matter."
	   Charlotte, which won consecutive games for the first time this
season, finishes at home against first-place Connecticut on
Saturday night. The Sting shot 50 percent, hitting at least half of
their shots for the third time this season.
	   Charlotte improved to 3-6 since Muggsy Bogues took over as coach
in place of Trudi Lacey, who remained as the team's general
manager.
	   "We're just trying to improve our team every time we step on
the floor," Bogues said. "They could have easily folded because
of the situation this season. These ladies understand what my
vision is, what my demeanor is and they've given me 110 percent."
	   Sam's steal and layup off the rebound of a missed free throw
capped Charlotte's 9-2 surge to open the second half, and the Sting
led 44-38 with 16:42 remaining. Johnson scored seven straight
points during the Liberty's 10-0 run that gave them a 56-52 lead
with 11:14 to play.
	   Caity Matter scored five straight points to give the Sting a
35-29 lead with 3:52 remaining in the first half.
	   New York closed the half with a 7-0 run, capped by Johnson's
jumper with 47 seconds left, to take a 36-35 lead at the break.
